metadata.name: Ornithic #99
metadata.description:
Pure p5.js code. No svg, no image, no other materials. Creating code arts with polar coordinate system and algorithms are my passion. This generative art contains a lot of features that may be rare than common.  

• 30 color palettes // 2 of them have 3 different colors
• 4 grass structures // With the same algorithm 
• 16 flower types //  Count, leaf number and size
• 6 color functions // Different colorizations with b&w 

Also, the outputs of the project are very high resolution to print or something like that.
April / 2022
Rhaegar

metadata.name: Sketching #38
metadata.description:
Rules : 
  1. Start with either a line or a circle from a number of random points in the space.
  2. A line can only spawn a circle at the end. 
  3. A circle can spawn both lines and circles before it completes the full circle.
  4. A circle can sometimes spawn an inner circle.
  5. Smaller elements will spawn randomly along with the lines.

This was inspired by the patterns in Marvel's movie : Eternals. I enjoyed the line growing animation with basic geometry ( line and circle ). Combining this with the rules It generates interesting results.

To add more variety to the rendering, I've added the dash lines in instead of only solid lines. Also the 'lines' consist of thousands of small dots to give it randomness and a bit of texture feeling.

metadata.name: Offset Disorder #67
metadata.description:
This work is an experiment using generated risograph halftones and hand-drawn elements to create a highly textured pattern. 

- Viewing in Chrome is recommended.
- Press ’s’ to save a screenshot. 
- Image size is 1200x1200px.

Common Features:
- Random 3 to 10 color palette using colors from p5riso
- Individual color layer shifts from 2 to 20px
- Simplex or square color noise patters
- Glitches resulting in hand-drawn shapes
- Glitch rate of 10-50% of shapes

Less Common
- Linear color distribution (top -> bottom)
- Up to 5 large hand-drawn circles
- Very high glitch rate of 50%

Rare
- Perfect color alignment with no errors

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0, see LICENSE.txt for more information.

metadata.name: Alma de Flor #34
metadata.description:
Alma de Flor is a project inspired by nature and floral afterlife. 

Plants are alive, they grow on our planet and populate almost every continent on earth. 
They live, grow and die. 
Some plants live a long time, some others don't. Kind of like humans, they change and evolve. They have souls, but they're different from ours, they differ in energy. 

Living in a tropical country allowed me to live in a place with huge biodiversity, so for me, this is how a born European, raised Latino person connects with this feeling.

metadata.name: Dream Recalls #11
metadata.description:
Based on 24 photographs taken with a kaleidoscope lens.
4 layers randomly blended & (sometimes) stretched to create new arrangements that seem like vague memories of a dream.

Altough the artwork is based on photographs, the algorithm allows for a high number of different outputs.
No traits.

Press "s" in live view to save your Dream Recall.

Photographs, process and code by k4leido_k1d
Twitter: @k4leido_k1d

metadata.name: Piastrelle #6
metadata.description:
Piastrelle is the Italian word for tiles, one of the oldest forms used for decorative art. They’ve been treasured for centuries due to their durability and stunning beauty, as embellishing touches both inside and outside of buildings of all types.

Examples of beautiful tile work can be found in mosaics, murals and more from the oldest civilizations to the present day. Ancient Egyptians, Assyrians, Babylonians, Chinese, Romans and Greeks favoured decorative tiles, and nowadays a wealth of amazing and varied floor and wall tile designs exist to suit all tastes.

This artwork attempts to dialogue with the ancient practice of tiles ornamentation, presenting fragments of tiled surfaces from an extinct civilization of the future, which once had their buildings decorated in all its glory.

Please be aware that there may be some pieces missing, not everything will stand the test of time.

Actions:

- [RETURN] saves current image
- [SPACE] saves large size image (7410 × 9880 px)

Remistura Studio, January 2022

metadata.name: Surrounding Things - 質生塵 #53
metadata.description:
- 
Coordinating with Taipei: Art Salon 'Ties' with VolumeDAO, the auction will drop to 9.9 tezos on 12/15 at 11:00 AM (CET).

配合台北 VA Hub ‘Ties’ with VolumeDAO 藝術沙龍，拍賣將在12/15台北時間晚上7點下降至 9.9 tezos，一同共襄盛舉。

-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

This artwork is part of a series that Alvis currently exhibiton in Shanghai Film Art Center.

The powerful strokes of pixels stack up on the screen, revealing textures reminiscent of rocks sculpted by water and time, and structures resembling the muscles and bones of living organisms. Colors blend skillfully, creating the illusion of light and shadow, yet allowing one to feel the chill of moonlight and the lingering warmth of the setting sun.

The artist seems to have observed the shaping and destruction of the world with a detached perspective. It is a piece of art that appears to be the result of prolonged contemplation, profound insights, and strength.
